e. They bring together many earlier types of narrative—court tales, military accounts, anecdotes, and stories about the divine origins of shrines and temples––joining book genres with parlor arts and the culture of itinerant storytellers and performers. The works presented here are organized into three thematically overlapping sections titled, “Monsters, Warriors, and Journeys to Other Worlds,” “Buddhist Tales,” and “Interspecies Affairs.” Each translation is prefaced by a short introduction, and the book features images from the original scroll paintings, illustrated manuscripts, and printed books.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aJapanese fictiony1185-1600. 0aJapanese prose literaturey1185-1600. 0aOtogi-zōshi. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh1 aKimbrough, Keller, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShirane, Haruo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kimb1844640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231545501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231545501.jpg  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles